  <pyrophoric_liquids hazard_type="physical">
    <hazard_name>Pyrophoric liquids</hazard_name>
    <hazard_id>9.0</hazard_id>
    <classification>Category 1</classification>
    <hazard_statement>Catches fire spontaneously if exposed to air</hazard_statement>
    <rationale>Classified into Category 1 since butyl lithium is pyrophoric in presence of air (Hommel (1996)). The following information is available in Hommel that "Concentrated butyllithium is pyrophoric and explodes on contact with water. After butyllithium solution dried up, pyrophoric hollow-substance is left." and "International transportation is made exclusively in the form of hydrocarbon solution. In this case, pentane, hexane or heptane is used. These solutions of butyllithium are easy to ignite, but are no more pyrophoric." (Hommel (1996)). </rationale>
    <signal_word>Danger</signal_word>
    <symbol>Flame</symbol>
  </pyrophoric_liquids>
